{
  "text": "Intestinal colonization with C. difficile, and disease, is common in neonatal piglets within 7 days of farrowing [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The most common clinical sign for CDI in livestock is diarrhea, which may be acute or chronic; however, many neonatal animals remain without clinical disease probably due to acquired colostral immunity . CDI may be self-limiting, intermittent, or continuous in nature. Piglets infected by C. difficile may present with a yellow pasty or watery, nonhemorrhagic diarrhea. Ostrich chicks often experience anorexia, weight loss [CITATION_4] , acute diarrhea, and sudden death within 3 days [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . CDI should be considered in the differential diagnosis in poultry, as one of many diarrheacausing enteropathogens [CITATION_7] . Obstipation and constipation, scrotal edema, and dyspnea occur uncommonly in piglets [CITATION_8] . In humans, CDI occurs in older people as neonates are thought not to have toxin receptors. Clinical presentation in humans is similar to animals and patients may present with malaise, abdominal pain, nausea, anorexia, watery diarrhea, low-grade fever, and peripheral leukocytosis [CITATION_9] .",
